voice_to_text: A robot just arrived on earth and found that the energy ball was missing. The ball accidentally rolled down the hallway and was picked up by a boy. Seeing the boy get on the school bus, the robot quickly chased after him just as he was catch up. His battery was running low, he could only watch the ball. Followed the car into the school. In order to retrieve the ball, the robot tried to enter the school, but a guard stopped him and he was forced to retreat. The robot tried to climb over the fence, but was caught by the guards again. He doesn't want to give up, but only has 1% battery left, so he walked into an electric car dealership. The manager mistook him for a human and greeted him warmly. The robot looked around and in the store saw a fully charged car. He urgently rushed towards it. Just as he walked to the door, he completely lost his motivation. The manager thought he would see the bottom of the car and praised his attention to detail. Seeing the robot didn't respond, the manager helped him into the car and then sat on it as well. He started introducing the car. At this moment, the robot unplugged the charging cable and inserted it into the charging port. As the current flows in, the robot quietly absorbs energy. The manager thought he was admiring the car, so he continued to introduce its features. The robot listened. Mindlessly, while secretly absorbing energy. Suddenly the car stalled. The manager was confused, thinking the employee had forgotten to charge. The robot quickly unplugged the cable, entering another vehicle. As he arrived, he plugged the charging cable into the charging port again. Soon the car also ran out of battery. They keep on change with robots. Charging himself one by one. The cars here all running out of electricity. Finally, the fully charged robot was energetic. He decided to find the guard again.

voice_to_text: This prisoner was about to be executed. The guards cut Jack's collar and walked him toward the guillotine. Everyone was surprised to see that Jack didn't show a single sign of fear. His calm reaction made the jailer suspicious. He suddenly remembered the human face masks found at Jack's house and a chill ran down his spine. He rushed to stop the execution. A day earlier, Mary kept lightly tapping her cheek with her finger. In reality, she was talking to Jack and Morse code. Jack, who looked completely expressionless, was actually blinking his eyes to respond. Mary took out a pen and started writing down the message Jack was sending. When their secret conversation ended, the judge announced Jack's death sentence. The crowd cheered in excitement. But at that very moment, a satisfied smile appeared on Mary's face. Jack stayed calm because he and Mary had already planned a big escape. Following Jack's instructions, Mary went to the third alley. She pressed the third brick on the wall and a hidden stone door slowly opened. Inside, Jack's sports car was waiting. She drove it 37 km away to a remote mountain location. A hidden tunnel opened, revealing Jack's secret hideout. As soon as Mary put on the code Jack had given her, a vault open. Inside was a pile of cash and several mysterious vials. Mary picked up a red and yellow vial, then followed the plan to the main government office. Dressed in a stunning outfit, she met The minister of justice, who was already obsessed with her, completely under her spell. The minister agreed to everything she whispered in his ear. On the table lay a newspaper with the headline announcing Jack's execution. Mary told him she wanted to see the face of the man everyone called a monster. At first, the minister refused, but in the end, he agreed on the condition that he would go with her that night. They arrived at the prison. The minister convinced Warden John to let them meet Jack under the pretext of interrogation. All three walked into the interrogation room. As soon as the door closed, Mary injected the minister with a drug that knocked him out. Then she unlocked Jack's handcuffs. While the minister lay unconscious, Mary placed a mask over his face, swapping his identity with Jack's. She walked Jack out of the room. He walked right past the cop who came to arrest him, got into Mary's car, and the two of them disappeared into the night.

voice_to_text: The longest secret you've ever kept. My best friend Vanessa has been dead for three years, but I still text her phone every single day. It started the week after her funeral. I was completely wrecked, barely functional. Vanessa and I had been inseparable since middle school. She was the sister I never had. We talked every day for 12 years straight. The night after we buried her, I was drunk on cheap wine and scrolling through our old text conversations without thinking. I typed, I can't believe you're gone and hit send to her number. My phone buzzed immediately. Who is this? I froze. Someone else had her number now. I quickly explained about Vanessa, how she'd passed away in a car accident, how I texted without thinking. The response came 20 minutes later. I'm so sorry for your loss. I'm Aaron. If texting this number helps you grieve, please don't stop because of me. So I didn't stop. Every morning at 7:00am, exactly when Vanessa and I used to exchange our daily good morning beautiful texts, I'd send updates to her number. Got the promotion at work today. You always said I'd make manager before 25. Went on another terrible tinder date. Remember how you used to screen my matches? Mom's asking when I'm bringing someone home for Christmas again. Wish you were here to be my girlfriend. Like senior year, Aaron never responded to these messages for two years. I just sent them into the void. Treating It like my personal diary. Sometimes I'd send photos of sunsets or my coffee, things Vanessa would have loved. I told that number about every breakup, every family fight, every small victory. My other friends thought I was crazy when they found out it's been two years. They'd say you need to move on. Las reglas del juego eran muy estrictas, no podía llamar a la policía ni podía retirarme a mitad del juego. Presa del pánico, corrí a una iglesia cercana para esconderme, pero otro asesino ya estaba dentro. En medio del caos, maté por error a una persona inocente. El verdadero asesino se disfrazó de pastor. Cerró las puertas de la iglesia desde dentro y me atacó con un martillo, pero el martillo quedó atascado en la puerta. Rápidamente lo encerré dentro y escapé, pero poco después el asesino volvió a golpearme la pierna. voice_to_text: Cuando estaba a punto de disparar, una bella mujer bloqueó mi visión como toda una profesional. Inmediatamente moví la mira hacia el objetivo, pero no pude resistir y volví a mirar a la bella mujer. Como resultado, mi pulso se disparó hasta 101. Me puse los auriculares y y escuché música para calmarme. Cuando la frecuencia cardíaca llega a 65, se puede lograr el disparo más preciso. Accioné el cerrojo con agilidad, apunté, alineé rápidamente al objetivo y apreté el gatillo, pero no esperaba que la bella mujer detuviera la bala. En ese instante. Quise disparar de nuevo, pero los guardias de seguridad ya habían corrido las cortinas. No tuve otra opción más que abandonar la misión y activar el plan de fuga. Recogí rápidamente mi equipo, me puse el casco para ocultar mi rostro, monté una moto eléctrica capaz de acelerar y frenar rápidamente en la ruta de escape. Tiré el silenciador a la alcantarilla. Al pasar junto a un camión de basura, rojé allí el arma del crimen. Al llegar al puente, cambié a caminar, lancé el casco al río y luego me dirigí a un pequeño hotel. Me quité toda la ropa y limpié cuidadosamente mi cuerpo. Las armas dejan restos de pólvora. Incluso me afeité la barba antes de irme, me rocié con perfume para ocultar el olor de la escena del crimen. Luego tomé un taxi y, tras asegurarme de que nadie me seguía, me dirigí al aeropuerto. Tiré la pistola en un contenedor de Basura como un asesino con 30 años de profesión. El motivo por el que nunca me habían atrapado era que cuidaba cada detalle a la perfección. Pensé que ya había escapado, pero vi que un perro policía parecía haberme detectado. Al darme cuenta de que algo iba mal, me di media vuelta y entré al baño. Volví a lavarme con detergente y tiré la pulsera inteligente. Pasé el control de seguridad sin problemas. Llamé a mi jefe para informar la misión. Se sorprendió pues era la primera vez en 30 años que fallaba, pero ahora solo podía volver a casa y esperar nuevas instrucciones. Al terminar la llamada, saqué la tarjeta SIM y aplasté el teléfono. Un teléfono para una sola llamada. Ese era mi principio de acción en el avión. No me relajé. Miré a mi alrededor y vi a un hombre sospechoso con gafas oscuras. Después de eso, seguí todos sus movimientos. Al notar que siempre aparecía cerca de mí, me puse de inmediato en guardia. Cancelé el siguiente vuelo y me alojé en un hotel cercano. Cuando llegó la comida, miré por la mirilla para asegurarme de que no había nadie cerca. Solo entonces abrí la puerta. Cuando el camarero se fue, cerré la puerta con llave. Ni siquiera probé la comida. Solo tomé un vaso y una tapa de olla. Puse el vaso en el pomo de la puerta y la tapa en el suelo para que si alguien entraba pudiera escucharlo. Al instante. Puse el Cuchillo sobre la mesa. Como defensa, pasé la noche en el sofá. Una vez que confirmé que era seguro, finalmente tomé el vuelo de regreso. Al llegar a mi destino, conduje hacia mi casa de campo. En el camino no olvidé vigilar el tráfico, en sentido contrario, no me quité las gafas de sol hasta casi llegar a casa. Sin embargo, justo al llegar a la puerta me di cuenta de que algo no estaba bien

voice_to_text: I wish I was beautiful. Renee stood before the wishing fountain, wishing she could become beautiful. However, the wish did not come true. Feeling insecure about her overweight figure, Renee found that even children would cry at the sight of her and stores would tell her they didn't carry her size. Working day after day in the basement, she wanted to change herself. Renee dreamed of applying for a receptionist position at the cosmetics company she admired, but the job requirements only deepened her insecurity. One evening, after watching a television show about wishes coming true, she braved a heavy rainstorm to revisit the park's wishing fountain. When her appearance remained unchanged, she walked away disappointed. Determined, she joined a gym. Encouraged by her trainer, Renee felt motivated and full of energy. In her excitement, she pedaled faster and faster on the exercise bike until she fell off and passed out. When Renee woke up, she seemed disoriented. She believed she now had slender arms and long, straight legs. She walked to the mirror, examining herself repeatedly, and even asked the trainer if she looked beautiful. The trainer didn't know how to respond, because in his eyes, Renee looked exactly the same as before. Now, convinced of her new beauty, Renee left the gym with confidence. She danced down the street and greeted pretty girls she passed, eager to share her transformation with her friends. She covered their mouths as soon as she saw them, afraid they might scream in Shock at her beauty. Her friends were utterly confused. With no idea what she was doing. Renee misunderstood their silence, thinking they simply didn't recognize her now that she was so gorgeous. To prove her identity, she showed them the tattoo on her ankle. Seeing her so convinced, her friends didn't argue. They assumed her newfound confidence came from the workouts. This only strengthened Renee's belief that she was now undeniably beautiful. The next day, armed with absolute confidence in her looks and figure, Renee went to interview for the receptionist job at the cosmetics company she had always admired. When the interviewer insisted the position wasn't suitable for her, Renee didn't lose heart. She firmly stated that working there as a receptionist was her only goal. My only real goal is to come here and help people feel the same way I feel. Moved by Renee's passion, the owner, Ali, offered her the job. Renee's wish had finally come true.

voice_to_text: Every night before bed, the boy would work out on his bed. But every time he did, the springs under the mattress would creak so loud it kept his parents up. They hadn't gotten a good night's sleep in months. The reason Ronaldo worked out so much, he was head over heels for Melina, the beautiful woman who just moved to town. When Melina first arrived, Ronaldo and all his friends were instantly drawn to her. The second he laid eyes on the stunning woman, he couldn't help but fall for her. For days after that, Ronaldo would hang out with his friends on the path Malina usually took, just to catch another glimpse of her. But just seeing her from afar wasn't enough anymore. He grew curious about what her life was like at home. So whenever he had free time, Ronaldo would hover near Malina's house, watching her through a pair of binoculars. Even at night, he'd sneak up into a tree and peek through a tiny crack in her window. One night, while he was spying on her as usual, he saw something he'd never forget. Molina was holding a photo frame of her husband, who was away at war, and dancing to music. That image stuck in Ronaldo's mind. The next day, he went out and bought the exact same record Malina had been playing that night. He lay on his bed, put the record on, and daydreamed about Malina being right there with him That's when the loud creaking of his bed springs started happening every single night. A few days later, though, Ronaldo walked past Molina's house and noticed a crowd of men hanging around outside. All of them staring intently at her windows like they were waiting for something. He asked around and found out the terrible news. Word had come from the front lines that Molina's husband was missing, presumed dead. Overnight, she'd become a widow. That's when Ronaldo realized something. Every man in town had been watching Molina just like he had ever since she moved there. She was so beautiful, no one could look away. But none of those men cared about how she felt now that she'd lost her husband. They only cared about her looks. Ronaldo was the only one who knew just how much Molina loved her husband. Sure enough, when he went to check on her, he found Molina collapsed on the floor, clutching her husband's photo and sobbing. Ronaldo's heart ached for her. He mustered up all his courage, walked into her room, and kissed her. Just a small, gentle one to comfort her. It was the only time they ever touched.

voice_to_text: What name did your family force on you that nearly ruined your life? My real name was Anakin Skywalker Smith. Not a nickname, not my middle name. That was my actual legal first and middle name printed on my birth certificate. My parents met at a Star Wars convention in 1997, got engaged at another convention, had a Star Wars themed wedding, and when I was born in 2002, they thought naming me after the main character would be the ultimate tribute to their favourite franchise. They love Star Wars so much they had a room in our house dedicated to collectibles. Spent thousands on replica lightsabers. Went to every movie premiere in full costume. When I was little, it didn't matter because kids didn't get the reference yet. Elementary school was manageable because most kids hadn't seen the movies. Teachers would smile awkwardly when they read my name, but nobody made it a big deal. Then Fourth Grade happened and the revenge of the Sith came out. Suddenly every kid in school knew exactly who Anakin Skywalker was and what he became. A kid named Marcus up in the cafeteria and yelled, there's Darth Vader! And the entire lunchroom lost it. Within days, kids started making breathing sounds when I walked by, doing forced show gestures, calling me the chosen one in this mocking tone. Someone put a Darth Vader mask in my locker. The jokes never stopped. Middle school destroyed me. Every single teacher who called roll would Pause at my name. Some would even laugh, thinking it was funny, like my parents did something clever. Kids who didn't know me would hear my name and immediately start quoting the movies. I ate lunch in the library because the cafeteria was constant harassment. Someone started a petition as a joke to get me to change my last name to Vader. It got a 150 signatures before a teacher confiscated it. I begged my parents to let me go by my middle name, Skywalker, but my dad said that's even worse. And my mom insisted I should be proud of such a unique, powerful name. They genuinely thought they'd given me this amazing gift. By eighth grade, I stopped introducing myself entirely. I just say, call me whatever you want, because I knew the second I said my real name, people would either laugh or immediately start making Star Wars references. I started skipping classes where substitute teachers might call my name out loud because I couldn't handle the attention anymore. High school was when everything fell apart. First day of freshman year, the principal read me

voice_to_text: He suddenly realized that the worst student in his class might actually be a long distance running prodigy. He had been following the boy by car for 10 whole minutes. The speedometer showed 12 miles per hour, yet the boy never slowed down. That left him a little stunned. Curious to see how far the kid could go, he kept driving behind him until the boy finally noticed. Why are you following me? You know how fast you were going. What are you, a cop? Can I give you a lift? No, but you can quit following me. As he watched the boy walk away, Jim fell into deep thought. The kid he just saw might really be something special. Back home, Jim started digging through old records. He compared times from previous state competitions, and the results shocked him. At that pace, the boy could easily rank among the top 10 runners in the entire state. And that's without proper running shoes. With the right gear, he might even be a champion. Jim felt like he had just discovered buried treasure. As a PE teacher and coach, finding a champion could change everything for him. His reputation, his pay, even his entire life could finally leave this small, forgotten town. This was McFarland, one of the poorest places in California. The only reason Jim ended up here was because he had no other choice. He used to be a promising coach, but after accidentally injuring a player during a Game. He was fired and labeled as hot tempered. No school wanted him anymore. Desperate for a job, he moved his entire family to this dusty little town. They were used to city life, so everyone struggled to adjust. There wasn't even a proper restaurant around. Not a single place selling burgers. Just tacos and burritos. Crime was bad, and Jim never felt safe. He hated everything about this place and wanted to leave that very day. But no other school would take him, so he had no choice but to stay and teach here. On his first day, he discovered just how undisciplined the students were. When he told them to warm up, three of them simply walked off, saying they had to go home to work on the farm. Jim didn't expect much anyway. He barely cared about the class. Just told the rest of them to jog a few laps and called it a day. But that's when he noticed something strange. These kids were good at running. Still, he didn't think much of it. Until one evening, driving home, he saw Thomas. The boy was running at 12 miles per hour again. Jim couldn't believe it. At that speed, Thomas could run a mile in five minutes. The world record for Marathon pace was just slightly faster. Thomas was a rare talent. The first time in a long while, Jim felt a spark of hope. If he could bring these runners together, form a cross country Team and lead them to victory. He might become a respected coach again. Maybe even find a better job elsewhere. He went straight to the principal with his idea. But the principal wasn't interested. There was no funding. That didn't stop Jim. California public school system pre approved six new sports a few years ago. How to get funding for new lockers, including guess what? Cross country. The principal finally agreed. Now that the team was approved, Jim needed runners in class. He set up a small race. The top four would each get a sports drink. The students jumped at the chance. After the run, Jim picked the best finishers and invited them to join his team. The first to say yes was Johnny, who already loved running. With Johnny's help, Jim Jim quickly recruited seven runners in total. Of course, Thomas was one of them. Training began, but every time Jim tried running with them, he was out of breath halfway through. Four kids who ran to school every day. Though this was nothing. They finished the drills easily. Watching them gulp down free tap water after training, Jim felt a pang of guilt. None of them even owned real running shoe. He said nothing, but he was deeply moved. To test their true ability, he soon registered them for a local race and bought them new uniforms and shoes. News. The boys were thrilled and full of confidence. But cross country was a team sport. Scores were Based on placement, one point for first, two for second, and so on. Only the top five runners from each team counted, and the lowest total score won. Before the race, other schools laughed at them. They came from McFarland, the forest town around. The boys felt humiliated, but also determined to prove themselves. When the race started, Thomas ran among the top three. Others were doing fine, too. On flat ground, Thomas was unbeatable. But when the hills came, his pace dropped fast. One after another, runners passed him. By the time he reached the finish line, he was outside the top 10. Their team came in last. Still, Jim took full responsibility. He blamed himself for not scouting the course earlier. He was disappointed, but not defeated. They had trained too lightly. The next day, he found a steep hill nearby that became their new training ground. The boys ran until they were gasping for air. When they asked to rest, Jim refused. He told them real victories come only through hard work. They kept running until they could barely stand. Only Thomas kept going, stubborn as ever. To him, no matter how much they trained, nothing would change their lives. Though those hills they ran on were made of almond shells. The same shells they had to shovel for work every day. To Thomas, training on them felt meaningless. Even if they won, they still end up in the fields. And he was right. These kids were All children of farm workers, many of them woke up at 5 to wash cars for extra money. Before sunset, they'd ride on trucks to pick crops. That was their life during school breaks. During the week, they got up at 4:30 every morning, climbed onto farm trucks half asleep, and spend hours bent over under the scorching sun. Only when school was about to start did they take off their hats and run through the dusty wind toward class. No wonder they were such strong runners. After learning all this, Jim made a promise to himself. He would help these kids run their way to a better life. He started studying everything he could about cross country. He watched old tapes, learning every technique. Then day after day, he passed that knowledge on, riding his pink bicycle alongside the team as they trained. Jim worked hard, and so did the boys. After weeks of training, Macfarlane High faced one of the best teams in the district. Before the race, Jim gathered his runners and lifted their spirits. Where are we from? Unola. Los Gladiators. We fought it. The race began. They fell behind at first, but their endurance carried them through. When other runners began to fade, Thomas stayed calm and focused. Near the end, he surged forward, passing everyone ahead. The rest of the team followed one by one. They won their very first race. No wild Celebration, just quiet hugs. But in their hearts, they knew this Victory meant everything. A few days later, trouble struck again. Three brothers, Danny and his siblings, suddenly quit the team. Jim went to their house to find out why, but their father shut the door on him. Cross countries like a TV, he said. It's not a necessity. Every hour my son spend training with you is an hour they could be helping me in the fields. You city people will never understand that. But Jim didn't give up. The next morning, as the brothers climbed onto the farm truck, they were shocked to see Jim sitting among them. Under the blazing sun, he bent down and picked cabbages beside them. By noon, he was exhausted. Only then did he truly understand how hard their lives were. So he made a deal with them. When you have to work late, we'll train afterward. And on days you need to harvest early, I'll come help. We'll make it work together. He kept his word, and soon the boy's mother noticed his effort. She wasn't easy to convince, but she had a kind heart. The next day, she organized a community fundraiser for the team. The townspeople, all Mexican immigrants, came together joyfully. They donated what little they could. Thanks to them, the team finally had proper uniforms and running shoes. With new gear, training went smoother than ever. From dusty hills to green fields, from golden wheat plains to shaded forests, boys ran everywhere, leaving their sweat and dreams behind. Jim Told them, if we keep winning, we'll make it to the state championship. I can't run for you. But if you want to win, you have to believe in yourselves and in each other. With that trust, they kept winning. Race after race, their names appeared in newspapers. Cross country gave them not only honor, but something even greater, hope. One day, an English teacher read aloud a piece written by Jose, one of the runners. We fly like blackbirds through the morning rain. We rise with the warm wind. When we run, we are the masters of the earth. Our souls soar high, speaking to the gods, watching the world from above. In that moment, we are no longer immigrants, no longer the foolish Mexicans they think we are. The teacher was moved to tears. He thanked Jim for changing their lives. Before the final race that could take them to state, Jim handed out college brochures. He told them, if you make it to college, you can earn enough to help your families for real. After so many wins, he had become the pride of McFarland. At the regional finals, all they needed was a top four finish to qualify. Right before the race, Jim received an offer from a prestigious high school. A chance to finally earn more and move away. But this time, he hesitated. He couldn't just walk away from these kids when the starting gun fired. Everything they had endured LED to this moment. Thomas took the lead, the others close behind. The hill that once broke them now felt like level ground. Thomas reached the final stretch, still in first place, but a glance over his shoulder made him stumble and fall. He got back up and ran as fast as he could, but finished second. One by one, the others crossed the line. Then came the tense moment of the final results. First place was announced, then second, then third. If they could just get fourth, they'd move on to state. But just then, Thomas turned to Jim and revealed a secret. A secret that would change all of their lives forever. Want to know what happened next? Follow me. The rest of the story is coming soon.

voice_to_text: After finishing my meal at my sister's restaurant, I was about to leave when the manager called out, sir, you haven't paid your Bill yet. I looked at the unfamiliar face, thinking he must be new and didn't recognize me, so I politely explained. Just put it on your boss's tab. She knows about it. The mail manager gave me a dismissive glance. Sir, this is a three Michelin star restaurant. We never allow tabs. He finished speaking, then handed me a printed Bill. I glanced down at it. A single meal, half a million dollars. Glow up cutlery maintenance fee $30,000 exclusive air purification fee $50,000 VIP emotional appeasement service fee $100,000 and a bunch of other ridiculous charges. I had no idea my sister ran such a rip off joint. I let out a sarcastic laugh. I'm Adrian Hayes, Miss Hayes's brother. If there's an issue, she can come home and talk to me. But he wouldn't back down. If you can't afford it, just say so. Don't try to piggyback on Miss Hayes's name. I've seen plenty of pretty boys trying to sponge off women. I texted my assistant. Astros, tell my sister, either fire this guy or I'm pulling all my investments. Sir, stop wasting everyone's time. Just pay. His tone was smug and cutting, as if he'd already labeled me a scoundrel trying to climb the ladder on a woman's coat tails. Several curious glances were already turning my way. I frowned, not wanting to Waste time on such a ridiculous matter? I pulled out my phone and dialed my sister's number directly, but all I got was a cold, busy signal. I tried again. Same result. It's a weekday. What's that girl up to? I put down my phone and looked straight at the aggressive man, repeating each word clearly. I'll say it again. My name is Adrian Hayes, and I am the biological brother of your boss, Serena Hayes. Her phone isn't answering right now. You can check her card. My photo and information are linked to it. I thought this was the most direct and effective way to solve the problem. But when the male manager heard my name, instead of verifying it, he burst into a loud, exaggerated and grating laugh. He laughed so hard he almost doubled over, drawing even more attention. Then he suddenly leaned in close, lowering his voice to a whisper only we could hear. Still pretending. I've seen your face in Serena's photo album a thousand times. You're that persistent creep who always tries to interfere with our lives. And now you have the nerve to show up at her restaurant and put your tab on her. Who do you think you are? I froze for a second, then glanced at his name tag. Brendan Miller. An overwhelming sense of exasperation washed over me. Serena's boyfriend. The one she'd been so secretive about. The one she wouldn't even let me see a single photo of it. Turned out to be this foolish, venomous man right in front of me. How could her taste be this bad? It dawned on me then. Today's half million dollar exorbitant Bill wasn't a misunderstanding at all. It was a premeditated humiliation. Before I could even speak, he completely lost his patience. If this gentleman insists on dining and dashing, we'll have to restrain him until the police arrive. He waved his hand and two burly security guards who had been standing nearby immediately stepped forward. They were two well trained, strong men, two fists against four hands. My resistance was quickly subdued and my arms were twisted tightly behind my back. I struggled violently, but couldn't break free from their professional hold. They ignored my furious gaze and the frightened looks of the other guests, roughly dragging me towards the back kitchen. Then I was violently shoved into the storeroom in the back, reeking of disinfectant and stale, greasy slop. The door slammed shut, cutting off all light and sound from outside in the dark. The male manager said nothing. He simply raised his leather clad foot and kicked me hard in the stomach. The excruciating pain made me grunt instantly, my stomach churning. That's for spending my woman's money! That's for meddling in her business! He yelled, his voice twisted by jealousy and rage. He looked down at me, then ordered the two burly men beat him! Teach him a lesson! The two security guards were clearly his cronies. They didn't hesitate, a relentless flurry of punches and kicks raining down on me. I gritted my teeth, swallowing every cry of pain. My bones felt like they were being crushed. Inch by inch, my internal organs dislodged. His taunts continued. Who do you think you are, huh? Just a good for nothing leeching off his sister? I told you, I'm her brother. If you don't believe me, ask Serena. Call her now. I'll talk to her. I struggled to explain, but the man in front of me just ignored it. It wasn't until I started feeling dizzy that he raised a hand, signaling them to stop. He nudged my shoulder with the tip of his leather shoe, looking at me triumphantly. You better settle the Bill today and cough up another half million. That's the consequence of you interfering in my relationship with Serena and spending her money. I'm not afraid of trouble. Serena will handle any fallout for me. I was curled in a ball of pain, weakly trying to argue. That's my own money, I told you. If you don't believe me, go ask her. His face changed. He kicked me, and the two security guards immediately understood, their punches and kicks raining down on me again. I knew he wouldn't listen to anything I said. If this continued, I could be seriously hurt. After I coughed up a mouthful of blood, I used my last ounce of strength to grope for my phone on the floor. Stop! I'll pay. He seemed satisfied with my submission, signaling the two security guards to stop, squatted down and patted my swollen cheek. See? Wouldn't it have been easier to just do that from the start? You chose the hard way. Two million, not a cent less. I lay sprawled on the cold floor, gasping for breath, my lungs burning. I ignored him and dialed my friend Leo Rodriguez's number. The phone was answered quickly. Leo, bring two million to my sister's restaurant. I need it now. Leo, on the other end, paused, then said something was wrong. Adrian, what's wrong, man? Your voice sounds. Don't ask, just hurry. I cut him off and hung up. Brendan's eyes instantly lit up at the mention of two million. A greedy glint flashed in them. He probably thought I was beaten into submission, offering more money to beg for mercy. The triumph on his face was now impossible to hide. Smart move. Leo's speed was astonishing. Soon the storeroom door was violently shoved open from the outside. Leo, accompanied by two bodyguards, strode in quickly. He was shocked to see the blood on my mouth, my disheveled clothes, and my pathetic posture propped up on the floor. He rushed over to help me up. I shook my head, subtly signalling him to stay silent, then took the bank card he handed me with the PIN attached and tossed it to the man. The man took the card and didn't bother me further. Waving his hand, if that's a fake card, I have countless ways to find you. Get lost! Enduring the excruciating pain throughout my body, I limped out of that sickening place, leaning on Leo's arm. When we reached the entrance, I thanked Leo. Thanks, Buddy. I'll get this sorted and pay you back quickly. He looked at me worriedly. Don't worry about the money. It's nothing. But what happened to you, I sneered. My sister found herself a fine boyfriend. I guess I have a score to settle with her. I pulled out my phone and found the number for the restaurant's assistant general manager, Mr. Peterson. Mr. Peterson was the restaurant's actual manager, someone I had personally recruited, and he was quite loyal to me. The call connected. I wasted no words, my voice devoid of emotion. You have 10 minutes to fire a manager named Brendan Miller. Otherwise Hayes Enterprises will withdraw all investment from the restaurant. Every last cent. Mr. Peterson, on the other end, was scared shitless the moment he heard my voice. He must have heard the weakness and the unusual edge in my voice as he agreed in quick, terrified succession. Not even daring to ask why, I hung up the phone and without a moment's pause, told Leo to take me straight to the police station. With the clearest, calmest logic, I recounted everything that had just happened to the officer who assisted me. After giving a detailed statement at the police station, I went to the hospital for an injury assessment. I held that thin report in my hand, and the fury of betrayal, as if fueled by hot oil, burned hotter and fiercer within me. I needed an explanation. I needed Serena Hayes to give me an explanation herself. My assistant found out Serena was at her villa. My driver and bodyguards arrived, and we headed straight for Serena's place. That villa was also a gift for me. However, when I arrived, I was greeted by blaring heavy metal music and the raucous sounds of men and women echoing through the doors and windows. She was throwing a party. No wonder she hadn't answered my calls. The villa's main door was ajar, and on a strange impulse, I didn't push it open immediately. Soon I heard a familiar male voice. It was Brendan Miller. He was pouring out his story to everyone, painting himself as a poor, helpless victim bullied by an arrogant third party, EMI, who then had the audacity to turn the tables and accuse him. I just asked him to pay the Bill, and he threw $2 million in my face, then found people to get me fired. Serena, he's gone too far. He doesn't respect you at all. He just wants to humiliate me. He just wants us to break up. Inside, Serena's circle of friends, mostly hangers on and troublemakers, echoed his outrage. Serena, in turn, was loudly comforting Brendan in her arms, her voice full of Tenderness and indulgence. Brendan, don't worry, I won't let you suffer this injustice. Then, as if to prove her resolve, she promised everyone confidently, when I get my hands on my brother, I'll make him beg for your forgiveness on his knees. Inside, those spoiled brats were still backing Brendan, shouting about how they would make me pay. Serena, just say the word and we'll go drag that bastard out right now! Yeah, let him know who truly owns this place! I couldn't listen anymore. I raised a hand and my bodyguard kicked open the villa's front door. The booming music screeched to a halt, the noisy laughter instantly vanishing. Dozens of stunned eyes all at once turn towards the doorway. No need to drag me out, I'm right here. Who wants to teach me a lesson? How to read part 2? Type the lower left corner of the video. Download it. Search my code to follow.
